How to map this into your 12‑day schedule
Given your background and 5–8h/day budget, a realistic approach:

Days 1–2 (arrays/two‑pointers/sliding window & hashing)

From lists 1–38 and 156–163, pick:

Day 1: 4 array/hash problems + 3 window/two‑pointer + 1 interval

Day 2: 3 window/two‑pointer + 2 interval + 2 array/hash

Focus: prefix sums, hash map patterns, two‑pointer invariants, sliding window templates.

Day 3 (binary search + sorting tricks + a couple of heaps)

4 binary search problems (39–50) + 2 heap problems (108–117) + 1 interval.

Day 4 (stack/monotonic & expression parsing)

6 problems from 51–62, emphasize:

Daily Temperatures, Car Fleet, Largest Rectangle, Maximal Rectangle, Longest Valid Parentheses, Evaluate RPN.

Day 5 (linked lists + LRU + one bit‑style / pointer trick)

5 problems from 63–72 (include LRU Cache, Reverse‑k Group, Find the Duplicate Number)

1–2 heap or greedy problems for variety.

Days 6–7 (trees & BST)

Day 6: traversal/level‑order/BS tree validity problems (73–87).

Day 7: tree DP / harder (76, 83, 88–92).

Aim for 6–7 tree problems/day, with at least one serialization / iterator / reconstruction.

Day 8 (graphs)

6–8 problems from 93–107, including:

Number of Islands, Clone Graph, Course Schedule I/II, Word Ladder, Network Delay Time, Redundant Connection.

Day 9 (backtracking + tries/advanced)

4–5 backtracking problems (118–127)

2 trie/advanced problems (146–147, 149 or 150).

Day 10 (DP)

5–6 1D DP (128–137)

2–3 2D DP (138–145).

For each, explicitly write the recurrence and state definition before coding.

Day 11 (intervals/greedy + review favorites)

4 interval/greedy problems (156–163).

3–4 problems you felt weak on earlier (choose from any category).

Day 12 (mock interview simulation)

Morning: 2 x 45‑minute “rounds”:

Round A: 1 array/string + 1 tree/graph.

Round B: 1 DP/backtracking + 1 intervals/heap.

Afternoon/evening: fix any bugs from mock, re‑do at least 2 problems completely from memory.

During all of this, keep a tiny “pattern notebook”: for each new problem, spend 2–3 minutes at the end writing:

Pattern(s) used

Time/space complexity

One sentence on the core trick

By the end of 12 days, you’ll have touched all major patterns that show up in coding interviews, and you’ll have 60–90 problems deeply internalized with another ~70–100 at least lightly exposed, which is in line with targeted, pattern‑based prep recommended for big‑tech interviews.

If you want, next step can be: share your current weak areas (e.g., “DP is weakest, graphs are strong”), and a custom 12‑day per‑day breakdown can be tuned more aggressively around that.

